        "body": "A bedroom has one job the other rooms don't: it has to help you stop. The kitchen wants you alert, the home office wants you sharp, the living room wants you sociable. The bedroom wants your nervous system to *power down* — and color is one of the few levers in the room that works on you before you've consciously noticed it. Get it right and you sink into the space. Get it wrong and you lie there at 11pm vaguely wired, blaming the mattress.\n\nI design bedrooms differently from every other room in the house, and almost all of it comes down to one principle: **low stimulation wins.** This is the room where I deliberately turn the dial down.\n\n## Why saturated, energizing color backfires here\n\nIn a kitchen I'll happily run a punchy navy island or a clay-red tile, because energy is the assignment. In a bedroom that same intensity works against you. Pure, saturated hues — a true cobalt, an emerald, a hot coral — hold your eye and keep a low hum of visual activity going. That's exactly what you don't want in a room you're trying to fall asleep in.\n\nSo I pull color toward the calm end of the spectrum and I take the saturation *out*. Not gray, dingy mud — softened, slightly grayed-down versions of pretty colors. A blue becomes a dusty `#B9C4CC` instead of a clear `#2E5C8A`. A green becomes a muted sage `#C7CEBE` instead of a vivid `#3FA34D`. The hue is still there; the shouting isn't. If you want the why behind this, the calm end of [the psychology of color](/blog/psychology-of-color-branding) is the relevant chapter — cool, desaturated, recessive colors genuinely read as restful, and that's not woo, it's how the eye and brain handle low-arousal stimuli.\n\nThere's room for warmth too — blush, greige, soft terracotta, putty — as long as it stays *muted and grounded* rather than bright. Warm or cool both work in a bedroom; loud doesn't. If you're unsure which way to lean, [warm vs cool colors](/blog/warm-vs-cool-colors) is worth a read, but the bedroom-specific rule is simpler: pick the temperature, then drain the intensity.\n\n## Soft contrast is the whole game\n\nHere's the move that separates a restful bedroom from a merely nice one: **keep the contrast low.** The walls, the bedding, the curtains, the big rug should sit close together in value — all in the same gentle mid-to-light band, with no jarring jump between them. A pale greige wall against soft oat linen against a muted sage throw is *quiet* because nothing fights. Drop a stark black headboard against a bright white wall and you've installed a visual alarm clock over your bed.\n\nThis is the one room where I sometimes break the [60-30-10 rule](/blog/60-30-10-rule-in-design) on purpose. The classic split — 60% dominant, 30% secondary, 10% punchy accent — assumes you *want* that 10% pop. In a bedroom I often soften the accent until it's barely an accent at all, more a 70-25-5 with a whisper of contrast rather than a snap. Tonal, layered, analogous schemes are your friends here; if \"analogous\" is fuzzy, [understanding color harmony](/blog/understanding-color-harmony) explains why neighboring hues feel so settled together.\n\n## The bed is the anchor — not the wall\n\nIn the [living room](/interior-color-palettes/living-room) the sofa or the floor usually leads. In the bedroom, the **bed is the visual center of gravity** — it's the largest object, it's where your eye lands from the door, and it's the thing you're literally lying in. So I anchor the palette to the bedding and headboard, then let the walls support them.\n\nThat's backwards from how most people shop. They paint first, then buy whatever duvet's on sale. Flip it. Decide on your bedding and headboard tones — the linen, the upholstered headboard, the throw at the foot — and choose a wall color that *recedes behind them*. The wall in a bedroom is a backdrop, not the star. A soft, slightly-deeper-than-you-think wall makes pale bedding glow; a too-bright wall makes the bed look gray and tired by comparison. An upholstered headboard in a muted clay or a faded indigo is one of my favorite ways to introduce the room's deepest tone without painting a thing.\n\nFor the order of operations — anchor first, pull a harmony around it, sanity-check the values — [how to choose a color palette](/blog/how-to-choose-a-color-palette) walks the full process. You can sample a photo of your actual duvet or headboard fabric in [the color palette generator](/color-palette-generator) and build the wall and accent tones outward from it, which is exactly how I'd start a real project.\n\n## You live in this room at night — so test it at night\n\nThis is the single most overlooked thing about bedrooms, and it's specific to this room. You experience the kitchen and office in daylight. **You experience the bedroom mostly in the dark, under warm lamplight** — the last thing you see before sleep and the first thing at a groggy 6am.\n\nSo test your color *then.* A swatch that looks perfect at 2pm tells you almost nothing about how the room feels at 10pm under a `2700K` bedside bulb. Warm lamplight pushes everything cream and amber: it can turn a cool gray faintly lilac, warm a sage toward olive, and make a crisp white go butter. I tape the sample by the bed and look at it under the actual lamp I'll use, after dark, before I commit to anything. Buy your bulbs and your paint as a set — cool `4000K`+ bulbs feel clinical in a bedroom and undo all your soft, warm work. Stay warm, around `2700K`.\n\n### North vs south light, for a room you wake up in\n\nOrientation matters everywhere, but the bedroom twist is *which* daylight you care about. A north-facing bedroom (northern hemisphere) gets cool, flat, bluish light all day — beautiful and even, but it can leave a cool palette feeling chilly and a little austere when you wake into it. There I warm things up: greige, blush-taupe, a creamier white, so the morning feels gentle rather than gray. A south-facing bedroom gets generous warm light, which flatters almost anything and lets you lean into cooler, deeper, dustier blues and greens without the room turning into a cave. East-facing bedrooms catch the actual sunrise — lovely if you wake early, brutal if you don't, so factor your blackout curtains into the color too. Choose for the moments you're actually in the room: groggy morning and quiet night, not midday when you're rarely there.\n\n## The mistakes I see in bedrooms specifically\n\n- **Treating the bedroom like a feature room.** A bold accent wall, a saturated statement color — the things that sing in a living room read as restless over a bed. Save the drama for downstairs.\n- **Painting before choosing the bedding.** The bed leads. Pick the headboard and linens, then the wall.\n- **Too much contrast at eye level.** Stark dark-on-light right where you lie looking at it keeps the eye busy. Keep the band around the bed tonal and close.\n- **Judging color only in daylight.** You sleep here. Test under warm lamplight after dark before you commit.\n- **Cool bulbs in a warm scheme.** A `5000K` \"daylight\" bulb in the nightstand lamp turns your cozy room into a hospital corridor.\n- **A wall brighter than the bedding.** The wall should recede *behind* the bed, not upstage it — go a half-step deeper or softer than the chip tempts you to.\n\nA restful bedroom isn't a color so much as a *low-energy state* you build out of muted hues, soft contrast, warm light, and a bed that anchors the whole thing. Browse the swatches below for a starting point, then take it back to the pillar — [Interior Color Palettes](/interior-color-palettes) — to see how it threads into the rest of the home, and peek at the [bathroom](/interior-color-palettes/bathroom) if you've got an ensuite you want to flow into the same calm.",
